Before you proceed with the organization of your shed, wait until a dry day and drag everything outside. Check the shed's structure carefully for any signs of damage and water entry. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/bb/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/bb/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Examine the contents you took outside carefully for any signs of water damage, as this may indicate a leak you can’t see. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/da/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/da/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Check for any pest attack, such as moth damage to any fabric stored in the shed. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/71/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-1Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-1Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/71/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-1Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-1Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Make sure that all chemicals are sealed, the containers are undamaged, and the labels are still legible. Repair any structural damage to the shed and give it a sweep out before you put everything back inside. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/23/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-1Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-1Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/23/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-1Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-1Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If it begins raining while your shed's contents are outdoors, throw a tarpaulin over the contents. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3c/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-1Bullet5.jpg/v4-460px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-1Bullet5.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3c/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-1Bullet5.jpg/v4-760px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-1Bullet5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Also, remember that chemicals should never be left in hot or direct sunlight, and mustn’t be allowed to leak into the ground or water. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/66/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-1Bullet6.jpg/v4-460px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-1Bullet6.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/66/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-1Bullet6.jpg/v4-760px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-1Bullet6.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Garden tools tend to come in all shapes and sizes, and so does the rest of the contents of many peoples’ sheds.Bundle some Velcro wrap around collections of garden canes or longer hand tools such as hoes and spades. This will hold them together. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/27/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/27/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Use tall boxes to store long tools that you rarely use. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6a/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6a/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If you have a messy shed, it’s probably because you have limited storage options within the shed. Consider the following solutions to improve your storage and raise things off the floor of your shed:Install shelves. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e5/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e5/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Install pegboard. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/ad/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/ad/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Install tool hooks or velcro tidy straps. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f7/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f7/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

A cheap shoe tidy hung on the back of the shed door adds valuable storage for smaller items. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/60/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-4Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-4Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/60/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-4Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-4Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Consider hanging items from the ceiling. For example, overhead storage racks, hooks, bike pulleys or lifts, or even jelly jars attached by their lids to the ceiling offer increased storage. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/62/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-4Bullet5.jpg/v4-460px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-4Bullet5.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/62/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-4Bullet5.jpg/v4-760px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-4Bullet5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Consider a fold-down workbench or get one with integrated storage cupboards underneath. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3d/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-4Bullet6.jpg/v4-460px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-4Bullet6.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3d/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-4Bullet6.jpg/v4-760px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-4Bullet6.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Don’t neglect to hang things from the roof. Here are some ideas for roof storage:
Bikes can go on a bike rack or pulley system on the ceiling. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0d/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-7Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-7Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0d/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-7Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-7Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Ladders can also rest in a simple frame holder you can hang from the ceiling. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/33/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-7Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-7Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/33/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-7Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-7Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Also, consider hanging a length of rigid plastic pipe such as a water pipe length from the ceiling. You can slot long narrow items such as garden canes or lengths of dowling rod into this. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7c/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-7Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-7Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7c/Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-7Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Organize-a-Messy-Garden-Shed-Step-7Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
